2847  return ArrayOrMatrixSubscriptExprBits.RBracketLoc;
2848  }
2849  void setRBracketLoc(SourceLocation L) {
2850  ArrayOrMatrixSubscriptExprBits.RBracketLoc = L;
2851  }
2852 
2853  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
2854  return T->getStmtClass() == MatrixSubscriptExprClass;
2855  }
2856 
2857  // Iterators
2858  child_range children() {
2859  return child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0] + END_EXPR);
2860  }
2861  const_child_range children() const {
2862  return const_child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0] + END_EXPR);
2863  }
2864 };
2865 
2866 /// CallExpr - Represents a function call (C99 6.5.2.2, C++ [expr.call]).
2867 /// CallExpr itself represents a normal function call, e.g., "f(x, 2)",
2868 /// while its subclasses may represent alternative syntax that (semantically)
2869 /// results in a function call. For example, CXXOperatorCallExpr is
2870 /// a subclass for overloaded operator calls that use operator syntax, e.g.,
2871 /// "str1 + str2" to resolve to a function call.
2872 class CallExpr : public Expr {
2873  enum { FN = 0, PREARGS_START = 1 };
2874 
2875  /// The number of arguments in the call expression.
2876  unsigned NumArgs;
2877 
2878  /// The location of the right parentheses. This has a different meaning for
2879  /// the derived classes of CallExpr.
2880  SourceLocation RParenLoc;
2881 
2882  // CallExpr store some data in trailing objects. However since CallExpr
2883  // is used a base of other expression classes we cannot use
2884  // llvm::TrailingObjects. Instead we manually perform the pointer arithmetic
2885  // and casts.
2886  //
2887  // The trailing objects are in order:
2888  //
2889  // * A single "Stmt *" for the callee expression.
2890  //
2891  // * An array of getNumPreArgs() "Stmt *" for the pre-argument expressions.
2892  //
2893  // * An array of getNumArgs() "Stmt *" for the argument expressions.
2894  //
2895  // * An optional of type FPOptionsOverride.
2896  //
2897  // Note that we store the offset in bytes from the this pointer to the start
2898  // of the trailing objects. It would be perfectly possible to compute it
2899  // based on the dynamic kind of the CallExpr. However 1.) we have plenty of
2900  // space in the bit-fields of Stmt. 2.) It was benchmarked to be faster to
2901  // compute this once and then load the offset from the bit-fields of Stmt,
2902  // instead of re-computing the offset each time the trailing objects are
2903  // accessed.
2904 
2905  /// Return a pointer to the start of the trailing array of "Stmt *".
2906  Stmt **getTrailingStmts() {
2907  return reinterpret_cast<Stmt **>(reinterpret_cast<char *>(this) +
2908  CallExprBits.OffsetToTrailingObjects);
2909  }
2910  Stmt *const *getTrailingStmts() const {
2911  return const_cast<CallExpr *>(this)->getTrailingStmts();
2912  }
2913 
2914  /// Map a statement class to the appropriate offset in bytes from the
2915  /// this pointer to the trailing objects.
2916  static unsigned offsetToTrailingObjects(StmtClass SC);
2917 
2918  unsigned getSizeOfTrailingStmts() const {
2919  return (1 + getNumPreArgs() + getNumArgs()) * sizeof(Stmt *);
2920  }
2921 
2922  size_t getOffsetOfTrailingFPFeatures() const {
2923  assert(hasStoredFPFeatures());
2924  return CallExprBits.OffsetToTrailingObjects + getSizeOfTrailingStmts();
2925  }
2926 
2927 public:
2928  enum class ADLCallKind : bool { NotADL, UsesADL };
2929  static constexpr ADLCallKind NotADL = ADLCallKind::NotADL;
2930  static constexpr ADLCallKind UsesADL = ADLCallKind::UsesADL;
2931 
2932 protected:
2933  /// Build a call expression, assuming that appropriate storage has been
2934  /// allocated for the trailing objects.
2935  CallExpr(StmtClass SC, Expr *Fn, ArrayRef<Expr *> PreArgs,
2936  ArrayRef<Expr *> Args, QualType Ty, ExprValueKind VK,
2937  SourceLocation RParenLoc, FPOptionsOverride FPFeatures,
2938  unsigned MinNumArgs, ADLCallKind UsesADL);
2939 
2940  /// Build an empty call expression, for deserialization.
2941  CallExpr(StmtClass SC, unsigned NumPreArgs, unsigned NumArgs,
2942  bool hasFPFeatures, EmptyShell Empty);
2943 
2944  /// Return the size in bytes needed for the trailing objects.
2945  /// Used by the derived classes to allocate the right amount of storage.
2946  static unsigned sizeOfTrailingObjects(unsigned NumPreArgs, unsigned NumArgs,
2947  bool HasFPFeatures) {
2948  return (1 + NumPreArgs + NumArgs) * sizeof(Stmt *) +
2949  HasFPFeatures * sizeof(FPOptionsOverride);
2950  }
2951 
2952  Stmt *getPreArg(unsigned I) {
2953  assert(I < getNumPreArgs() && "Prearg access out of range!");
2954  return getTrailingStmts()[PREARGS_START + I];
2955  }
2956  const Stmt *getPreArg(unsigned I) const {
2957  assert(I < getNumPreArgs() && "Prearg access out of range!");
2958  return getTrailingStmts()[PREARGS_START + I];
2959  }
2960  void setPreArg(unsigned I, Stmt *PreArg) {
2961  assert(I < getNumPreArgs() && "Prearg access out of range!");
2962  getTrailingStmts()[PREARGS_START + I] = PreArg;
2963  }
2964 
2965  unsigned getNumPreArgs() const { return CallExprBits.NumPreArgs; }
2966 
2967  /// Return a pointer to the trailing FPOptions
2968  FPOptionsOverride *getTrailingFPFeatures() {
2969  assert(hasStoredFPFeatures());
2970  return reinterpret_cast<FPOptionsOverride *>(
2971  reinterpret_cast<char *>(this) + CallExprBits.OffsetToTrailingObjects +
2972  getSizeOfTrailingStmts());
2973  }
2974  const FPOptionsOverride *getTrailingFPFeatures() const {
2975  assert(hasStoredFPFeatures());
2976  return reinterpret_cast<const FPOptionsOverride *>(
2977  reinterpret_cast<const char *>(this) +
2978  CallExprBits.OffsetToTrailingObjects + getSizeOfTrailingStmts());
2979  }
2980 
2981 public:
2982  /// Create a call expression.
2983  /// \param Fn The callee expression,
2984  /// \param Args The argument array,
2985  /// \param Ty The type of the call expression (which is *not* the return
2986  /// type in general),
2987  /// \param VK The value kind of the call expression (lvalue, rvalue, ...),
2988  /// \param RParenLoc The location of the right parenthesis in the call
2989  /// expression.
2990  /// \param FPFeatures Floating-point features associated with the call,
2991  /// \param MinNumArgs Specifies the minimum number of arguments. The actual
2992  /// number of arguments will be the greater of Args.size()
2993  /// and MinNumArgs. This is used in a few places to allocate
2994  /// enough storage for the default arguments.
2995  /// \param UsesADL Specifies whether the callee was found through
2996  /// argument-dependent lookup.
2997  ///
2998  /// Note that you can use CreateTemporary if you need a temporary call
2999  /// expression on the stack.
3000  static CallExpr *Create(const ASTContext &Ctx, Expr *Fn,
3001  ArrayRef<Expr *> Args, QualType Ty, ExprValueKind VK,
3002  SourceLocation RParenLoc,
3003  FPOptionsOverride FPFeatures, unsigned MinNumArgs = 0,
3004  ADLCallKind UsesADL = NotADL);
3005 
3006  /// Create a temporary call expression with no arguments in the memory
3007  /// pointed to by Mem. Mem must points to at least sizeof(CallExpr)
3008  /// + sizeof(Stmt *) bytes of storage, aligned to alignof(CallExpr):
3009  ///
3010  /// \code{.cpp}

3081  /// Compute and set dependence bits.
3082  void computeDependence() {
3083  setDependence(clang::computeDependence(
3084  this, llvm::ArrayRef(
3085  reinterpret_cast<Expr **>(getTrailingStmts() + PREARGS_START),
3086  getNumPreArgs())));
3087  }
3088 
3089  /// Reduce the number of arguments in this call expression. This is used for
3090  /// example during error recovery to drop extra arguments. There is no way
3091  /// to perform the opposite because: 1.) We don't track how much storage
3092  /// we have for the argument array 2.) This would potentially require growing
3093  /// the argument array, something we cannot support since the arguments are
3094  /// stored in a trailing array.
3095  void shrinkNumArgs(unsigned NewNumArgs) {
3096  assert((NewNumArgs <= getNumArgs()) &&
3097  "shrinkNumArgs cannot increase the number of arguments!");
3098  NumArgs = NewNumArgs;
3099  }

3101  /// Bluntly set a new number of arguments without doing any checks whatsoever.
3102  /// Only used during construction of a CallExpr in a few places in Sema.
3103  /// FIXME: Find a way to remove it.
3104  void setNumArgsUnsafe(unsigned NewNumArgs) { NumArgs = NewNumArgs; }

3602  typedef const CXXBaseSpecifier *const *path_const_iterator;
3603  bool path_empty() const { return path_size() == 0; }
3604  unsigned path_size() const { return CastExprBits.BasePathSize; }
3605  path_iterator path_begin() { return path_buffer(); }
3606  path_iterator path_end() { return path_buffer() + path_size(); }
3607  path_const_iterator path_begin() const { return path_buffer(); }
3608  path_const_iterator path_end() const { return path_buffer() + path_size(); }

3610  /// Path through the class hierarchy taken by casts between base and derived
3611  /// classes (see implementation of `CastConsistency()` for a full list of
3612  /// cast kinds that have a path).
3613  ///
3614  /// For each derived-to-base edge in the path, the path contains a
3615  /// `CXXBaseSpecifier` for the base class of that edge; the entries are
3616  /// ordered from derived class to base class.
3617  ///
3618  /// For example, given classes `Base`, `Intermediate : public Base` and
3619  /// `Derived : public Intermediate`, the path for a cast from `Derived *` to
3620  /// `Base *` contains two entries: One for `Intermediate`, and one for `Base`,
3621  /// in that order.
3622  llvm::iterator_range<path_iterator> path() {
3623  return llvm::make_range(path_begin(), path_end());
3624  }
3625  llvm::iterator_range<path_const_iterator> path() const {
3626  return llvm::make_range(path_begin(), path_end());
3627  }
3628 
3629  const FieldDecl *getTargetUnionField() const {
3630  assert(getCastKind() == CK_ToUnion);
3631  return getTargetFieldForToUnionCast(getType(), getSubExpr()->getType());
3632  }
3633 
3634  bool hasStoredFPFeatures() const { return CastExprBits.HasFPFeatures; }
3635 
3636  /// Get FPOptionsOverride from trailing storage.
3637  FPOptionsOverride getStoredFPFeatures() const {
3638  assert(hasStoredFPFeatures());
3639  return *getTrailingFPFeatures();
3640  }
3641 
3642  /// Get the FP features status of this operation. Only meaningful for
3643  /// operations on floating point types.
3644  FPOptions getFPFeaturesInEffect(const LangOptions &LO) const {
3645  if (hasStoredFPFeatures())
3646  return getStoredFPFeatures().applyOverrides(LO);
3647  return FPOptions::defaultWithoutTrailingStorage(LO);
3648  }
3649 
3650  FPOptionsOverride getFPFeatures() const {
3651  if (hasStoredFPFeatures())
3652  return getStoredFPFeatures();
3653  return FPOptionsOverride();
3654  }
3655 
3656  /// Return
3657  // True : if this conversion changes the volatile-ness of a gl-value.
3658  // Qualification conversions on gl-values currently use CK_NoOp, but
3659  // it's important to recognize volatile-changing conversions in
3660  // clients code generation that normally eagerly peephole loads. Note
3661  // that the query is answering for this specific node; Sema may
3662  // produce multiple cast nodes for any particular conversion sequence.
3663  // False : Otherwise.
3664  bool changesVolatileQualification() const {
3665  return (isGLValue() && (getType().isVolatileQualified() !=
3666  getSubExpr()->getType().isVolatileQualified()));
3667  }
3668 
3669  static const FieldDecl *getTargetFieldForToUnionCast(QualType unionType,
3670  QualType opType);
3671  static const FieldDecl *getTargetFieldForToUnionCast(const RecordDecl *RD,
3672  QualType opType);
3673 
3674  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
3675  return T->getStmtClass() >= firstCastExprConstant &&
3676  T->getStmtClass() <= lastCastExprConstant;
3677  }
3678 
3679  // Iterators
3680  child_range children() { return child_range(&Op, &Op+1); }
3681  const_child_range children() const { return const_child_range(&Op, &Op + 1); }
3682 };

3684 /// ImplicitCastExpr - Allows us to explicitly represent implicit type
3685 /// conversions, which have no direct representation in the original
3686 /// source code. For example: converting T[]->T*, void f()->void
3687 /// (*f)(), float->double, short->int, etc.
3688 ///
3689 /// In C, implicit casts always produce rvalues. However, in C++, an
3690 /// implicit cast whose result is being bound to a reference will be
3691 /// an lvalue or xvalue. For example:
3692 ///
3693 /// @code
3694 /// class Base { };
3695 /// class Derived : public Base { };
3696 /// Derived &&ref();
3697 /// void f(Derived d) {
3698 /// Base& b = d; // initializer is an ImplicitCastExpr
3699 /// // to an lvalue of type Base
3700 /// Base&& r = ref(); // initializer is an ImplicitCastExpr
3701 /// // to an xvalue of type Base
3702 /// }
3703 /// @endcode
3704 class ImplicitCastExpr final
3705  : public CastExpr,
3706  private llvm::TrailingObjects<ImplicitCastExpr, CXXBaseSpecifier *,
3707  FPOptionsOverride> {
3708 
3709  ImplicitCastExpr(QualType ty, CastKind kind, Expr *op,
3710  unsigned BasePathLength, FPOptionsOverride FPO,
3711  ExprValueKind VK)
3712  : CastExpr(ImplicitCastExprClass, ty, VK, kind, op, BasePathLength,
3713  FPO.requiresTrailingStorage()) {
3714  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
3715  if (hasStoredFPFeatures())
3716  *getTrailingFPFeatures() = FPO;
3717  }
3718 
3719  /// Construct an empty implicit cast.
3720  explicit ImplicitCastExpr(EmptyShell Shell, unsigned PathSize,
3721  bool HasFPFeatures)
3722  : CastExpr(ImplicitCastExprClass, Shell, PathSize, HasFPFeatures) {}
3723 
3724  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<CXXBaseSpecifier *>) const {
3725  return path_size();
3726  }
3727 
3728 public:
3729  enum OnStack_t { OnStack };
3730  ImplicitCastExpr(OnStack_t _, QualType ty, CastKind kind, Expr *op,
3731  ExprValueKind VK, FPOptionsOverride FPO)
3732  : CastExpr(ImplicitCastExprClass, ty, VK, kind, op, 0,
3733  FPO.requiresTrailingStorage()) {
3734  if (hasStoredFPFeatures())
3735  *getTrailingFPFeatures() = FPO;
3736  }
3737 
3738  bool isPartOfExplicitCast() const { return CastExprBits.PartOfExplicitCast; }
3739  void setIsPartOfExplicitCast(bool PartOfExplicitCast) {
3740  CastExprBits.PartOfExplicitCast = PartOfExplicitCast;
3741  }
3742 
3743  static ImplicitCastExpr *Create(const ASTContext &Context, QualType T,
3744  CastKind Kind, Expr *Operand,
3745  const CXXCastPath *BasePath,
3746  ExprValueKind Cat, FPOptionsOverride FPO);
3747 
3748  static ImplicitCastExpr *CreateEmpty(const ASTContext &Context,
3749  unsigned PathSize, bool HasFPFeatures);
3750 
3751  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
3752  return getSubExpr()->getBeginLoc();
3753  }
3754  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
3755  return getSubExpr()->getEndLoc();
3756  }
3757 
3758  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
3759  return T->getStmtClass() == ImplicitCastExprClass;
3760  }
3761 
3762  friend TrailingObjects;
3763  friend class CastExpr;
3764 };

3766 /// ExplicitCastExpr - An explicit cast written in the source
3767 /// code.
3768 ///
3769 /// This class is effectively an abstract class, because it provides
3770 /// the basic representation of an explicitly-written cast without
3771 /// specifying which kind of cast (C cast, functional cast, static
3772 /// cast, etc.) was written; specific derived classes represent the
3773 /// particular style of cast and its location information.
3774 ///
3775 /// Unlike implicit casts, explicit cast nodes have two different
3776 /// types: the type that was written into the source code, and the
3777 /// actual type of the expression as determined by semantic
3778 /// analysis. These types may differ slightly. For example, in C++ one
3779 /// can cast to a reference type, which indicates that the resulting
3780 /// expression will be an lvalue or xvalue. The reference type, however,
3781 /// will not be used as the type of the expression.
3782 class ExplicitCastExpr : public CastExpr {
3783  /// TInfo - Source type info for the (written) type
3784  /// this expression is casting to.
3785  TypeSourceInfo *TInfo;
3786 
3787 protected:
3788  ExplicitCastExpr(StmtClass SC, QualType exprTy, ExprValueKind VK,
3789  CastKind kind, Expr *op, unsigned PathSize,
3790  bool HasFPFeatures, TypeSourceInfo *writtenTy)
3791  : CastExpr(SC, exprTy, VK, kind, op, PathSize, HasFPFeatures),
3792  TInfo(writtenTy) {
3793  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
3794  }
3795 
3796  /// Construct an empty explicit cast.
3797  ExplicitCastExpr(StmtClass SC, EmptyShell Shell, unsigned PathSize,
3798  bool HasFPFeatures)
3799  : CastExpr(SC, Shell, PathSize, HasFPFeatures) {}
3800 
3801 public:
3802  /// getTypeInfoAsWritten - Returns the type source info for the type
3803  /// that this expression is casting to.
3804  TypeSourceInfo *getTypeInfoAsWritten() const { return TInfo; }
3805  void setTypeInfoAsWritten(TypeSourceInfo *writtenTy) { TInfo = writtenTy; }
3806 
3807  /// getTypeAsWritten - Returns the type that this expression is
3808  /// casting to, as written in the source code.
3809  QualType getTypeAsWritten() const { return TInfo->getType(); }
3810 
3811  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
3812  return T->getStmtClass() >= firstExplicitCastExprConstant &&
3813  T->getStmtClass() <= lastExplicitCastExprConstant;
3814  }
3815 };

3874 /// A builtin binary operation expression such as "x + y" or "x <= y".
3875 ///
3876 /// This expression node kind describes a builtin binary operation,
3877 /// such as "x + y" for integer values "x" and "y". The operands will
3878 /// already have been converted to appropriate types (e.g., by
3879 /// performing promotions or conversions).
3880 ///
3881 /// In C++, where operators may be overloaded, a different kind of
3882 /// expression node (CXXOperatorCallExpr) is used to express the
3883 /// invocation of an overloaded operator with operator syntax. Within
3884 /// a C++ template, whether BinaryOperator or CXXOperatorCallExpr is
3885 /// used to store an expression "x + y" depends on the subexpressions
3886 /// for x and y. If neither x or y is type-dependent, and the "+"
3887 /// operator resolves to a built-in operation, BinaryOperator will be
3888 /// used to express the computation (x and y may still be
3889 /// value-dependent). If either x or y is type-dependent, or if the
3890 /// "+" resolves to an overloaded operator, CXXOperatorCallExpr will
3891 /// be used to express the computation.
3892 class BinaryOperator : public Expr {
3893  enum { LHS, RHS, END_EXPR };
3894  Stmt *SubExprs[END_EXPR];
3895 
3896 public:
3897  typedef BinaryOperatorKind Opcode;
3898 
3899 protected:
3900  size_t offsetOfTrailingStorage() const;
3901 
3902  /// Return a pointer to the trailing FPOptions
3903  FPOptionsOverride *getTrailingFPFeatures() {
3904  assert(BinaryOperatorBits.HasFPFeatures);
3905  return reinterpret_cast<FPOptionsOverride *>(
3906  reinterpret_cast<char *>(this) + offsetOfTrailingStorage());
3907  }
3908  const FPOptionsOverride *getTrailingFPFeatures() const {
3909  assert(BinaryOperatorBits.HasFPFeatures);
3910  return reinterpret_cast<const FPOptionsOverride *>(
3911  reinterpret_cast<const char *>(this) + offsetOfTrailingStorage());
3912  }
3913 
3914  /// Build a binary operator, assuming that appropriate storage has been
3915  /// allocated for the trailing objects when needed.
3916  BinaryOperator(const ASTContext &Ctx, Expr *lhs, Expr *rhs, Opcode opc,
3917  QualType ResTy, ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK,
3918  SourceLocation opLoc, FPOptionsOverride FPFeatures);
3919 
3920  /// Construct an empty binary operator.
3921  explicit BinaryOperator(EmptyShell Empty) : Expr(BinaryOperatorClass, Empty) {
3922  BinaryOperatorBits.Opc = BO_Comma;
3923  }

3997  static Opcode negateComparisonOp(Opcode Opc) {
3998  switch (Opc) {
3999  default:
4000  llvm_unreachable("Not a comparison operator.");
4001  case BO_LT: return BO_GE;
4002  case BO_GT: return BO_LE;
4003  case BO_LE: return BO_GT;
4004  case BO_GE: return BO_LT;
4005  case BO_EQ: return BO_NE;
4006  case BO_NE: return BO_EQ;
4007  }
4008  }
4009 
4010  static Opcode reverseComparisonOp(Opcode Opc) {
4011  switch (Opc) {
4012  default:
4013  llvm_unreachable("Not a comparison operator.");
4014  case BO_LT: return BO_GT;
4015  case BO_GT: return BO_LT;
4016  case BO_LE: return BO_GE;
4017  case BO_GE: return BO_LE;
4018  case BO_EQ:
4019  case BO_NE:
4020  return Opc;
4021  }
4022  }

4038  static Opcode getOpForCompoundAssignment(Opcode Opc) {
4039  assert(isCompoundAssignmentOp(Opc));
4040  if (Opc >= BO_AndAssign)

4042  else

4044  }

4134 /// CompoundAssignOperator - For compound assignments (e.g. +=), we keep
4135 /// track of the type the operation is performed in. Due to the semantics of
4136 /// these operators, the operands are promoted, the arithmetic performed, an
4137 /// implicit conversion back to the result type done, then the assignment takes
4138 /// place. This captures the intermediate type which the computation is done
4139 /// in.
4140 class CompoundAssignOperator : public BinaryOperator {
4141  QualType ComputationLHSType;
4142  QualType ComputationResultType;
4143 
4144  /// Construct an empty CompoundAssignOperator.
4145  explicit CompoundAssignOperator(const ASTContext &C, EmptyShell Empty,
4146  bool hasFPFeatures)
4147  : BinaryOperator(CompoundAssignOperatorClass, Empty) {}
4148 
4149 protected:
4150  CompoundAssignOperator(const ASTContext &C, Expr *lhs, Expr *rhs, Opcode opc,
4151  QualType ResType, ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK,
4152  SourceLocation OpLoc, FPOptionsOverride FPFeatures,
4153  QualType CompLHSType, QualType CompResultType)
4154  : BinaryOperator(C, lhs, rhs, opc, ResType, VK, OK, OpLoc, FPFeatures,
4155  true),
4156  ComputationLHSType(CompLHSType), ComputationResultType(CompResultType) {
4157  assert(isCompoundAssignmentOp() &&
4158  "Only should be used for compound assignments");
4159  }
4160 
4161 public:
4162  static CompoundAssignOperator *CreateEmpty(const ASTContext &C,
4163  bool hasFPFeatures);
4164 
4165  static CompoundAssignOperator *
4166  Create(const ASTContext &C, Expr *lhs, Expr *rhs, Opcode opc, QualType ResTy,
4167  ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK, SourceLocation opLoc,
4168  FPOptionsOverride FPFeatures, QualType CompLHSType = QualType(),
4169  QualType CompResultType = QualType());
4170 
4171  // The two computation types are the type the LHS is converted
4172  // to for the computation and the type of the result; the two are
4173  // distinct in a few cases (specifically, int+=ptr and ptr-=ptr).
4174  QualType getComputationLHSType() const { return ComputationLHSType; }
4175  void setComputationLHSType(QualType T) { ComputationLHSType = T; }
4176 
4177  QualType getComputationResultType() const { return ComputationResultType; }
4178  void setComputationResultType(QualType T) { ComputationResultType = T; }
4179 
4180  static bool classof(const Stmt *S) {
4181  return S->getStmtClass() == CompoundAssignOperatorClass;
4182  }
4183 };
4184 
4185 inline size_t BinaryOperator::offsetOfTrailingStorage() const {
4186  assert(BinaryOperatorBits.HasFPFeatures);
4187  return isa<CompoundAssignOperator>(this) ? sizeof(CompoundAssignOperator)
4188  : sizeof(BinaryOperator);
4189 }

4191 /// AbstractConditionalOperator - An abstract base class for
4192 /// ConditionalOperator and BinaryConditionalOperator.
4193 class AbstractConditionalOperator : public Expr {
4194  SourceLocation QuestionLoc, ColonLoc;
4195  friend class ASTStmtReader;
4196 
4197 protected:
4198  AbstractConditionalOperator(StmtClass SC, QualType T, ExprValueKind VK,
4199  ExprObjectKind OK, SourceLocation qloc,
4200  SourceLocation cloc)

4202 
4203  AbstractConditionalOperator(StmtClass SC, EmptyShell Empty)
4204  : Expr(SC, Empty) { }
4205 
4206 public:
4207  /// getCond - Return the expression representing the condition for
4208  /// the ?: operator.

4210

4212  /// the expression if the condition evaluates to true.
4213  Expr *getTrueExpr() const;
4214 
4215  /// getFalseExpr - Return the subexpression representing the value of
4216  /// the expression if the condition evaluates to false. This is
4217  /// the same as getRHS.
4218  Expr *getFalseExpr() const;
4219

4221  SourceLocation getColonLoc() const { return ColonLoc; }
4222 
4223  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
4224  return T->getStmtClass() == ConditionalOperatorClass ||
4225  T->getStmtClass() == BinaryConditionalOperatorClass;
4226  }
4227 };

4229 /// ConditionalOperator - The ?: ternary operator. The GNU "missing
4230 /// middle" extension is a BinaryConditionalOperator.
4231 class ConditionalOperator : public AbstractConditionalOperator {
4232  enum { COND, LHS, RHS, END_EXPR };
4233  Stmt* SubExprs[END_EXPR]; // Left/Middle/Right hand sides.
4234 
4235  friend class ASTStmtReader;
4236 public:
4237  ConditionalOperator(Expr *cond, SourceLocation QLoc, Expr *lhs,
4238  SourceLocation CLoc, Expr *rhs, QualType t,
4239  ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK)
4240  : AbstractConditionalOperator(ConditionalOperatorClass, t, VK, OK, QLoc,
4241  CLoc) {
4242  SubExprs[COND] = cond;
4243  SubExprs[LHS] = lhs;
4244  SubExprs[RHS] = rhs;
4245  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
4246  }
4247 
4248  /// Build an empty conditional operator.
4249  explicit ConditionalOperator(EmptyShell Empty)
4250  : AbstractConditionalOperator(ConditionalOperatorClass, Empty) { }
4251 
4252  /// getCond - Return the expression representing the condition for
4253  /// the ?: operator.
4254  Expr *getCond() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[COND]); }
4255 
4256  /// getTrueExpr - Return the subexpression representing the value of
4257  /// the expression if the condition evaluates to true.
4258  Expr *getTrueExpr() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[LHS]); }
4259 
4260  /// getFalseExpr - Return the subexpression representing the value of
4261  /// the expression if the condition evaluates to false. This is
4262  /// the same as getRHS.
4263  Expr *getFalseExpr() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[RHS]); }
4264 
4265  Expr *getLHS() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[LHS]); }
4266  Expr *getRHS() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[RHS]); }
4267 
4268  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
4269  return getCond()->getBeginLoc();
4270  }
4271  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
4272  return getRHS()->getEndLoc();
4273  }
4274 
4275  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
4276  return T->getStmtClass() == ConditionalOperatorClass;
4277  }
4278 
4279  // Iterators
4280  child_range children() {
4281  return child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0]+END_EXPR);
4282  }
4283  const_child_range children() const {
4284  return const_child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0] + END_EXPR);
4285  }
4286 };

4288 /// BinaryConditionalOperator - The GNU extension to the conditional
4289 /// operator which allows the middle operand to be omitted.
4290 ///
4291 /// This is a different expression kind on the assumption that almost
4292 /// every client ends up needing to know that these are different.
4293 class BinaryConditionalOperator : public AbstractConditionalOperator {
4294  enum { COMMON, COND, LHS, RHS, NUM_SUBEXPRS };
4295 
4296  /// - the common condition/left-hand-side expression, which will be
4297  /// evaluated as the opaque value
4298  /// - the condition, expressed in terms of the opaque value
4299  /// - the left-hand-side, expressed in terms of the opaque value
4300  /// - the right-hand-side
4301  Stmt *SubExprs[NUM_SUBEXPRS];
4302  OpaqueValueExpr *OpaqueValue;
4303 
4304  friend class ASTStmtReader;
4305 public:
4306  BinaryConditionalOperator(Expr *common, OpaqueValueExpr *opaqueValue,
4307  Expr *cond, Expr *lhs, Expr *rhs,
4308  SourceLocation qloc, SourceLocation cloc,
4309  QualType t, ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK)
4310  : AbstractConditionalOperator(BinaryConditionalOperatorClass, t, VK, OK,
4311  qloc, cloc),
4312  OpaqueValue(opaqueValue) {
4313  SubExprs[COMMON] = common;
4314  SubExprs[COND] = cond;
4315  SubExprs[LHS] = lhs;
4316  SubExprs[RHS] = rhs;
4317  assert(OpaqueValue->getSourceExpr() == common && "Wrong opaque value");
4318  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
4319  }
4320 
4321  /// Build an empty conditional operator.
4322  explicit BinaryConditionalOperator(EmptyShell Empty)
4323  : AbstractConditionalOperator(BinaryConditionalOperatorClass, Empty) { }
4324 
4325  /// getCommon - Return the common expression, written to the
4326  /// left of the condition. The opaque value will be bound to the
4327  /// result of this expression.
4328  Expr *getCommon() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[COMMON]); }
4329 
4330  /// getOpaqueValue - Return the opaque value placeholder.
4331  OpaqueValueExpr *getOpaqueValue() const { return OpaqueValue; }
4332 
4333  /// getCond - Return the condition expression; this is defined
4334  /// in terms of the opaque value.
4335  Expr *getCond() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[COND]); }
4336 
4337  /// getTrueExpr - Return the subexpression which will be
4338  /// evaluated if the condition evaluates to true; this is defined
4339  /// in terms of the opaque value.
4340  Expr *getTrueExpr() const {
4341  return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[LHS]);
4342  }
4343 
4344  /// getFalseExpr - Return the subexpression which will be
4345  /// evaluated if the condnition evaluates to false; this is
4346  /// defined in terms of the opaque value.
4347  Expr *getFalseExpr() const {
4348  return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[RHS]);
4349  }
4350 
4351  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
4352  return getCommon()->getBeginLoc();
4353  }
4354  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
4355  return getFalseExpr()->getEndLoc();
4356  }
4357 
4358  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
4359  return T->getStmtClass() == BinaryConditionalOperatorClass;
4360  }
4361 
4362  // Iterators
4363  child_range children() {
4364  return child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + NUM_SUBEXPRS);
4365  }
4366  const_child_range children() const {
4367  return const_child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + NUM_SUBEXPRS);
4368  }
4369 };
4370 
4371 inline Expr *AbstractConditionalOperator::getCond() const {
4372  if (const ConditionalOperator *co = dyn_cast<ConditionalOperator>(this))
4373  return co->getCond();
4374  return cast<BinaryConditionalOperator>(this)->getCond();
4375 }
4376 
4377 inline Expr *AbstractConditionalOperator::getTrueExpr() const {
4378  if (const ConditionalOperator *co = dyn_cast<ConditionalOperator>(this))
4379  return co->getTrueExpr();
4380  return cast<BinaryConditionalOperator>(this)->getTrueExpr();
4381 }
4382 
4383 inline Expr *AbstractConditionalOperator::getFalseExpr() const {
4384  if (const ConditionalOperator *co = dyn_cast<ConditionalOperator>(this))
4385  return co->getFalseExpr();
4386  return cast<BinaryConditionalOperator>(this)->getFalseExpr();
4387 }

4477 /// ShuffleVectorExpr - clang-specific builtin-in function
4478 /// __builtin_shufflevector.
4479 /// This AST node represents a operator that does a constant

4483 class ShuffleVectorExpr : public Expr {

4488  // indices. The number of values in this list is always
4489  // 2+the number of indices in the vector type.
4490  Stmt **SubExprs;
4491  unsigned NumExprs;
4492 
4493 public:
4494  ShuffleVectorExpr(const ASTContext &C, ArrayRef<Expr*> args, QualType Type,
4495  SourceLocation BLoc, SourceLocation RP);
4496 
4497  /// Build an empty vector-shuffle expression.
4498  explicit ShuffleVectorExpr(EmptyShell Empty)
4499  : Expr(ShuffleVectorExprClass, Empty), SubExprs(nullptr) { }
4500

4502  void setBuiltinLoc(SourceLocation L) { BuiltinLoc = L; }
4503 
4504  SourceLocation getRParenLoc() const { return RParenLoc; }
4505  void setRParenLoc(SourceLocation L) { RParenLoc = L; }
4506 
4507  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return BuiltinLoc; }
4508  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return RParenLoc; }
4509

4511  return T->getStmtClass() == ShuffleVectorExprClass;
4512  }
4513 
4514  /// getNumSubExprs - Return the size of the SubExprs array. This includes the
4515  /// constant expression, the actual arguments passed in, and the function
4516  /// pointers.
4517  unsigned getNumSubExprs() const { return NumExprs; }
4518 
4519  /// Retrieve the array of expressions.
4520  Expr **getSubExprs() { return reinterpret_cast<Expr **>(SubExprs); }
4521 
4522  /// getExpr - Return the Expr at the specified index.
4523  Expr *getExpr(unsigned Index) {
4524  assert((Index < NumExprs) && "Arg access out of range!");
4525  return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[Index]);
4526  }
4527  const Expr *getExpr(unsigned Index) const {
4528  assert((Index < NumExprs) && "Arg access out of range!");
4529  return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[Index]);
4530  }
4531

4533 
4534  llvm::APSInt getShuffleMaskIdx(const ASTContext &Ctx, unsigned N) const {
4535  assert((N < NumExprs - 2) && "Shuffle idx out of range!");
4536  return getExpr(N+2)->EvaluateKnownConstInt(Ctx);
4537  }
4538 
4539  // Iterators
4540  child_range children() {
4541  return child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0]+NumExprs);
4542  }
4543  const_child_range children() const {
4544  return const_child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0] + NumExprs);
4545  }

4601 /// ChooseExpr - GNU builtin-in function __builtin_choose_expr.
4602 /// This AST node is similar to the conditional operator (?:) in C, with
4603 /// the following exceptions:
4604 /// - the test expression must be a integer constant expression.
4605 /// - the expression returned acts like the chosen subexpression in every
4606 /// visible way: the type is the same as that of the chosen subexpression,
4607 /// and all predicates (whether it's an l-value, whether it's an integer
4608 /// constant expression, etc.) return the same result as for the chosen
4609 /// sub-expression.
4610 class ChooseExpr : public Expr {
4611  enum { COND, LHS, RHS, END_EXPR };
4612  Stmt* SubExprs[END_EXPR]; // Left/Middle/Right hand sides.
4613  SourceLocation BuiltinLoc, RParenLoc;
4614  bool CondIsTrue;
4615 public:
4616  ChooseExpr(SourceLocation BLoc, Expr *cond, Expr *lhs, Expr *rhs, QualType t,
4617  ExprValueKind VK, ExprObjectKind OK, SourceLocation RP,
4618  bool condIsTrue)
4619  : Expr(ChooseExprClass, t, VK, OK), BuiltinLoc(BLoc), RParenLoc(RP),
4620  CondIsTrue(condIsTrue) {
4621  SubExprs[COND] = cond;
4622  SubExprs[LHS] = lhs;
4623  SubExprs[RHS] = rhs;
4624 
4625  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
4626  }
4627 
4628  /// Build an empty __builtin_choose_expr.
4629  explicit ChooseExpr(EmptyShell Empty) : Expr(ChooseExprClass, Empty) { }
4630 
4631  /// isConditionTrue - Return whether the condition is true (i.e. not
4632  /// equal to zero).
4633  bool isConditionTrue() const {
4634  assert(!isConditionDependent() &&
4635  "Dependent condition isn't true or false");
4636  return CondIsTrue;
4637  }
4638  void setIsConditionTrue(bool isTrue) { CondIsTrue = isTrue; }
4639 
4640  bool isConditionDependent() const {
4641  return getCond()->isTypeDependent() || getCond()->isValueDependent();
4642  }
4643 
4644  /// getChosenSubExpr - Return the subexpression chosen according to the
4645  /// condition.
4646  Expr *getChosenSubExpr() const {
4647  return isConditionTrue() ? getLHS() : getRHS();
4648  }
4649 
4650  Expr *getCond() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[COND]); }
4651  void setCond(Expr *E) { SubExprs[COND] = E; }
4652  Expr *getLHS() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[LHS]); }
4653  void setLHS(Expr *E) { SubExprs[LHS] = E; }
4654  Expr *getRHS() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[RHS]); }
4655  void setRHS(Expr *E) { SubExprs[RHS] = E; }
4656 
4657  SourceLocation getBuiltinLoc() const { return BuiltinLoc; }
4658  void setBuiltinLoc(SourceLocation L) { BuiltinLoc = L; }
4659 
4660  SourceLocation getRParenLoc() const { return RParenLoc; }
4661  void setRParenLoc(SourceLocation L) { RParenLoc = L; }
4662 
4663  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return BuiltinLoc; }
4664  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY { return RParenLoc; }
4665 
4666  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
4667  return T->getStmtClass() == ChooseExprClass;
4668  }
4669 
4670  // Iterators
4671  child_range children() {
4672  return child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0]+END_EXPR);
4673  }
4674  const_child_range children() const {
4675  return const_child_range(&SubExprs[0], &SubExprs[0] + END_EXPR);
4676  }
4677 };

4727  TInfo(TInfo, IsMS), BuiltinLoc(BLoc), RParenLoc(RPLoc) {
4728  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
4729  }

4736  Expr *getSubExpr() { return cast<Expr>(Val); }

4842 
4843 /// Describes an C or C++ initializer list.
4844 ///
4845 /// InitListExpr describes an initializer list, which can be used to
4846 /// initialize objects of different types, including
4847 /// struct/class/union types, arrays, and vectors. For example:
4848 ///
4849 /// @code
4850 /// struct foo x = { 1, { 2, 3 } };
4851 /// @endcode
4852 ///
4853 /// Prior to semantic analysis, an initializer list will represent the
4854 /// initializer list as written by the user, but will have the
4855 /// placeholder type "void". This initializer list is called the
4856 /// syntactic form of the initializer, and may contain C99 designated
4857 /// initializers (represented as DesignatedInitExprs), initializations
4858 /// of subobject members without explicit braces, and so on. Clients
4859 /// interested in the original syntax of the initializer list should
4860 /// use the syntactic form of the initializer list.
4861 ///
4862 /// After semantic analysis, the initializer list will represent the
4863 /// semantic form of the initializer, where the initializations of all
4864 /// subobjects are made explicit with nested InitListExpr nodes and
4865 /// C99 designators have been eliminated by placing the designated
4866 /// initializations into the subobject they initialize. Additionally,
4867 /// any "holes" in the initialization, where no initializer has been
4868 /// specified for a particular subobject, will be replaced with
4869 /// implicitly-generated ImplicitValueInitExpr expressions that
4870 /// value-initialize the subobjects. Note, however, that the
4871 /// initializer lists may still have fewer initializers than there are
4872 /// elements to initialize within the object.
4873 ///
4874 /// After semantic analysis has completed, given an initializer list,
4875 /// method isSemanticForm() returns true if and only if this is the
4876 /// semantic form of the initializer list (note: the same AST node
4877 /// may at the same time be the syntactic form).
4878 /// Given the semantic form of the initializer list, one can retrieve
4879 /// the syntactic form of that initializer list (when different)
4880 /// using method getSyntacticForm(); the method returns null if applied
4881 /// to a initializer list which is already in syntactic form.
4882 /// Similarly, given the syntactic form (i.e., an initializer list such
4883 /// that isSemanticForm() returns false), one can retrieve the semantic
4884 /// form using method getSemanticForm().
4885 /// Since many initializer lists have the same syntactic and semantic forms,
4886 /// getSyntacticForm() may return NULL, indicating that the current
4887 /// semantic initializer list also serves as its syntactic form.
4888 class InitListExpr : public Expr {
4889  // FIXME: Eliminate this vector in favor of ASTContext allocation
4890  typedef ASTVector<Stmt *> InitExprsTy;
4891  InitExprsTy InitExprs;
4892  SourceLocation LBraceLoc, RBraceLoc;
4893 
4894  /// The alternative form of the initializer list (if it exists).
4895  /// The int part of the pair stores whether this initializer list is
4896  /// in semantic form. If not null, the pointer points to:
4897  /// - the syntactic form, if this is in semantic form;
4898  /// - the semantic form, if this is in syntactic form.
4899  llvm::PointerIntPair<InitListExpr *, 1, bool> AltForm;
4900 
4901  /// Either:
4902  /// If this initializer list initializes an array with more elements than
4903  /// there are initializers in the list, specifies an expression to be used
4904  /// for value initialization of the rest of the elements.
4905  /// Or
4906  /// If this initializer list initializes a union, specifies which
4907  /// field within the union will be initialized.
4908  llvm::PointerUnion<Expr *, FieldDecl *> ArrayFillerOrUnionFieldInit;
4909 
4910 public:
4911  InitListExpr(const ASTContext &C, SourceLocation lbraceloc,
4912  ArrayRef<Expr*> initExprs, SourceLocation rbraceloc);
4913 
4914  /// Build an empty initializer list.
4915  explicit InitListExpr(EmptyShell Empty)
4916  : Expr(InitListExprClass, Empty), AltForm(nullptr, true) { }
4917 
4918  unsigned getNumInits() const { return InitExprs.size(); }
4919 
4920  /// Retrieve the set of initializers.
4921  Expr **getInits() { return reinterpret_cast<Expr **>(InitExprs.data()); }
4922 
4923  /// Retrieve the set of initializers.
4924  Expr * const *getInits() const {
4925  return reinterpret_cast<Expr * const *>(InitExprs.data());
4926  }
4927 
4928  ArrayRef<Expr *> inits() { return llvm::ArrayRef(getInits(), getNumInits()); }
4929 
4930  ArrayRef<Expr *> inits() const {
4931  return llvm::ArrayRef(getInits(), getNumInits());
4932  }
4933 
4934  const Expr *getInit(unsigned Init) const {
4935  assert(Init < getNumInits() && "Initializer access out of range!");
4936  return cast_or_null<Expr>(InitExprs[Init]);
4937  }
4938 
4939  Expr *getInit(unsigned Init) {
4940  assert(Init < getNumInits() && "Initializer access out of range!");
4941  return cast_or_null<Expr>(InitExprs[Init]);
4942  }
4943 
4944  void setInit(unsigned Init, Expr *expr) {
4945  assert(Init < getNumInits() && "Initializer access out of range!");
4946  InitExprs[Init] = expr;
4947 
4948  if (expr)
4949  setDependence(getDependence() | expr->getDependence());
4950  }
4951 
4952  /// Mark the semantic form of the InitListExpr as error when the semantic
4953  /// analysis fails.
4954  void markError() {
4955  assert(isSemanticForm());
4956  setDependence(getDependence() | ExprDependence::ErrorDependent);
4957  }
4958 
4959  /// Reserve space for some number of initializers.
4960  void reserveInits(const ASTContext &C, unsigned NumInits);
4961 
4962  /// Specify the number of initializers
4963  ///
4964  /// If there are more than @p NumInits initializers, the remaining
4965  /// initializers will be destroyed. If there are fewer than @p
4966  /// NumInits initializers, NULL expressions will be added for the
4967  /// unknown initializers.
4968  void resizeInits(const ASTContext &Context, unsigned NumInits);
4969 
4970  /// Updates the initializer at index @p Init with the new
4971  /// expression @p expr, and returns the old expression at that
4972  /// location.
4973  ///
4974  /// When @p Init is out of range for this initializer list, the
4975  /// initializer list will be extended with NULL expressions to
4976  /// accommodate the new entry.
4977  Expr *updateInit(const ASTContext &C, unsigned Init, Expr *expr);
4978 
4979  /// If this initializer list initializes an array with more elements
4980  /// than there are initializers in the list, specifies an expression to be
4981  /// used for value initialization of the rest of the elements.
4982  Expr *getArrayFiller() {
4983  return ArrayFillerOrUnionFieldInit.dyn_cast<Expr *>();
4984  }
4985  const Expr *getArrayFiller() const {
4986  return const_cast<InitListExpr *>(this)->getArrayFiller();
4987  }
4988  void setArrayFiller(Expr *filler);
4989 
4990  /// Return true if this is an array initializer and its array "filler"
4991  /// has been set.
4992  bool hasArrayFiller() const { return getArrayFiller(); }
4993 
4994  /// Determine whether this initializer list contains a designated initializer.
4995  bool hasDesignatedInit() const {
4996  return std::any_of(begin(), end(), [](const Stmt *S) {
4997  return isa<DesignatedInitExpr>(S);
4998  });
4999  }
5000 
5001  /// If this initializes a union, specifies which field in the
5002  /// union to initialize.
5003  ///
5004  /// Typically, this field is the first named field within the
5005  /// union. However, a designated initializer can specify the
5006  /// initialization of a different field within the union.
5007  FieldDecl *getInitializedFieldInUnion() {
5008  return ArrayFillerOrUnionFieldInit.dyn_cast<FieldDecl *>();
5009  }
5010  const FieldDecl *getInitializedFieldInUnion() const {
5011  return const_cast<InitListExpr *>(this)->getInitializedFieldInUnion();
5012  }
5013  void setInitializedFieldInUnion(FieldDecl *FD) {
5014  assert((FD == nullptr
5015  || getInitializedFieldInUnion() == nullptr
5016  || getInitializedFieldInUnion() == FD)
5017  && "Only one field of a union may be initialized at a time!");
5018  ArrayFillerOrUnionFieldInit = FD;
5019  }
5020 
5021  // Explicit InitListExpr's originate from source code (and have valid source
5022  // locations). Implicit InitListExpr's are created by the semantic analyzer.
5023  // FIXME: This is wrong; InitListExprs created by semantic analysis have
5024  // valid source locations too!
5025  bool isExplicit() const {
5026  return LBraceLoc.isValid() && RBraceLoc.isValid();
5027  }
5028 
5029  /// Is this an initializer for an array of characters, initialized by a string
5030  /// literal or an @encode?
5031  bool isStringLiteralInit() const;
5032 
5033  /// Is this a transparent initializer list (that is, an InitListExpr that is
5034  /// purely syntactic, and whose semantics are that of the sole contained
5035  /// initializer)?
5036  bool isTransparent() const;
5037 
5038  /// Is this the zero initializer {0} in a language which considers it
5039  /// idiomatic?
5040  bool isIdiomaticZeroInitializer(const LangOptions &LangOpts) const;
5041 
5042  SourceLocation getLBraceLoc() const { return LBraceLoc; }
5043  void setLBraceLoc(SourceLocation Loc) { LBraceLoc = Loc; }
5044  SourceLocation getRBraceLoc() const { return RBraceLoc; }
5045  void setRBraceLoc(SourceLocation Loc) { RBraceLoc = Loc; }
5046 
5047  bool isSemanticForm() const { return AltForm.getInt(); }
5048  InitListExpr *getSemanticForm() const {
5049  return isSemanticForm() ? nullptr : AltForm.getPointer();
5050  }
5051  bool isSyntacticForm() const {
5052  return !AltForm.getInt() || !AltForm.getPointer();
5053  }
5054  InitListExpr *getSyntacticForm() const {
5055  return isSemanticForm() ? AltForm.getPointer() : nullptr;
5056  }
5057 
5058  void setSyntacticForm(InitListExpr *Init) {
5059  AltForm.setPointer(Init);
5060  AltForm.setInt(true);
5061  Init->AltForm.setPointer(this);
5062  Init->AltForm.setInt(false);
5063  }
5064 
5065  bool hadArrayRangeDesignator() const {
5066  return InitListExprBits.HadArrayRangeDesignator != 0;
5067  }
5068  void sawArrayRangeDesignator(bool ARD = true) {
5069  InitListExprBits.HadArrayRangeDesignator = ARD;
5070  }
5071 
5072  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY;
5073  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY;
5074 
5075  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
5076  return T->getStmtClass() == InitListExprClass;
5077  }
5078 
5079  // Iterators
5080  child_range children() {
5081  const_child_range CCR = const_cast<const InitListExpr *>(this)->children();
5082  return child_range(cast_away_const(CCR.begin()),
5083  cast_away_const(CCR.end()));
5084  }
5085 
5086  const_child_range children() const {
5087  // FIXME: This does not include the array filler expression.
5088  if (InitExprs.empty())
5089  return const_child_range(const_child_iterator(), const_child_iterator());
5090  return const_child_range(&InitExprs[0], &InitExprs[0] + InitExprs.size());
5091  }
5092 
5093  typedef InitExprsTy::iterator iterator;
5094  typedef InitExprsTy::const_iterator const_iterator;
5095  typedef InitExprsTy::reverse_iterator reverse_iterator;
5096  typedef InitExprsTy::const_reverse_iterator const_reverse_iterator;
5097 
5098  iterator begin() { return InitExprs.begin(); }
5099  const_iterator begin() const { return InitExprs.begin(); }
5100  iterator end() { return InitExprs.end(); }
5101  const_iterator end() const { return InitExprs.end(); }
5102  reverse_iterator rbegin() { return InitExprs.rbegin(); }
5103  const_reverse_iterator rbegin() const { return InitExprs.rbegin(); }
5104  reverse_iterator rend() { return InitExprs.rend(); }
5105  const_reverse_iterator rend() const { return InitExprs.rend(); }
5106 
5107  friend class ASTStmtReader;
5108  friend class ASTStmtWriter;
5109 };
5110 
5111 /// Represents a C99 designated initializer expression.
5112 ///
5113 /// A designated initializer expression (C99 6.7.8) contains one or
5114 /// more designators (which can be field designators, array
5115 /// designators, or GNU array-range designators) followed by an
5116 /// expression that initializes the field or element(s) that the
5117 /// designators refer to. For example, given:
5118 ///
5119 /// @code
5120 /// struct point {
5121 /// double x;
5122 /// double y;
5123 /// };
5124 /// struct point ptarray[10] = { [2].y = 1.0, [2].x = 2.0, [0].x = 1.0 };
5125 /// @endcode
5126 ///
5127 /// The InitListExpr contains three DesignatedInitExprs, the first of
5128 /// which covers @c [2].y=1.0. This DesignatedInitExpr will have two
5129 /// designators, one array designator for @c [2] followed by one field
5130 /// designator for @c .y. The initialization expression will be 1.0.
5131 class DesignatedInitExpr final
5132  : public Expr,
5133  private llvm::TrailingObjects<DesignatedInitExpr, Stmt *> {
5134 public:
5135  /// Forward declaration of the Designator class.
5136  class Designator;
5137 
5138 private:
5139  /// The location of the '=' or ':' prior to the actual initializer
5140  /// expression.
5141  SourceLocation EqualOrColonLoc;
5142 
5143  /// Whether this designated initializer used the GNU deprecated
5144  /// syntax rather than the C99 '=' syntax.
5145  LLVM_PREFERRED_TYPE(bool)
5146  unsigned GNUSyntax : 1;
5147 
5148  /// The number of designators in this initializer expression.
5149  unsigned NumDesignators : 15;
5150 
5151  /// The number of subexpressions of this initializer expression,
5152  /// which contains both the initializer and any additional
5153  /// expressions used by array and array-range designators.
5154  unsigned NumSubExprs : 16;
5155 
5156  /// The designators in this designated initialization
5157  /// expression.
5158  Designator *Designators;
5159 
5160  DesignatedInitExpr(const ASTContext &C, QualType Ty,
5161  llvm::ArrayRef<Designator> Designators,
5162  SourceLocation EqualOrColonLoc, bool GNUSyntax,
5163  ArrayRef<Expr *> IndexExprs, Expr *Init);
5164 
5165  explicit DesignatedInitExpr(unsigned NumSubExprs)
5166  : Expr(DesignatedInitExprClass, EmptyShell()),
5167  NumDesignators(0), NumSubExprs(NumSubExprs), Designators(nullptr) { }
5168 
5169 public:
5170  /// Represents a single C99 designator.
5171  ///
5172  /// @todo This class is infuriatingly similar to clang::Designator,
5173  /// but minor differences (storing indices vs. storing pointers)
5174  /// keep us from reusing it. Try harder, later, to rectify these
5175  /// differences.
5176  class Designator {
5177  /// A field designator, e.g., ".x".
5178  struct FieldDesignatorInfo {
5179  /// Refers to the field that is being initialized. The low bit
5180  /// of this field determines whether this is actually a pointer
5181  /// to an IdentifierInfo (if 1) or a FieldDecl (if 0). When
5182  /// initially constructed, a field designator will store an
5183  /// IdentifierInfo*. After semantic analysis has resolved that
5184  /// name, the field designator will instead store a FieldDecl*.
5185  uintptr_t NameOrField;
5186 
5187  /// The location of the '.' in the designated initializer.
5188  SourceLocation DotLoc;
5189 
5190  /// The location of the field name in the designated initializer.
5191  SourceLocation FieldLoc;
5192 
5193  FieldDesignatorInfo(const IdentifierInfo *II, SourceLocation DotLoc,
5194  SourceLocation FieldLoc)
5195  : NameOrField(reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(II) | 0x1), DotLoc(DotLoc),
5196  FieldLoc(FieldLoc) {}
5197  };
5198 
5199  /// An array or GNU array-range designator, e.g., "[9]" or "[10...15]".
5200  struct ArrayOrRangeDesignatorInfo {
5201  /// Location of the first index expression within the designated
5202  /// initializer expression's list of subexpressions.
5203  unsigned Index;
5204 
5205  /// The location of the '[' starting the array range designator.
5206  SourceLocation LBracketLoc;
5207 
5208  /// The location of the ellipsis separating the start and end
5209  /// indices. Only valid for GNU array-range designators.
5210  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc;
5211 
5212  /// The location of the ']' terminating the array range designator.
5213  SourceLocation RBracketLoc;
5214 
5215  ArrayOrRangeDesignatorInfo(unsigned Index, SourceLocation LBracketLoc,
5216  SourceLocation RBracketLoc)
5217  : Index(Index), LBracketLoc(LBracketLoc), RBracketLoc(RBracketLoc) {}
5218 
5219  ArrayOrRangeDesignatorInfo(unsigned Index,
5220  SourceLocation LBracketLoc,
5221  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc,
5222  SourceLocation RBracketLoc)
5223  : Index(Index), LBracketLoc(LBracketLoc), EllipsisLoc(EllipsisLoc),
5224  RBracketLoc(RBracketLoc) {}
5225  };
5226 
5227  /// The kind of designator this describes.
5228  enum DesignatorKind {
5229  FieldDesignator,
5230  ArrayDesignator,
5231  ArrayRangeDesignator
5232  };
5233 
5234  DesignatorKind Kind;
5235 
5236  union {
5237  /// A field designator, e.g., ".x".
5238  struct FieldDesignatorInfo FieldInfo;
5239 
5240  /// An array or GNU array-range designator, e.g., "[9]" or "[10..15]".
5241  struct ArrayOrRangeDesignatorInfo ArrayOrRangeInfo;
5242  };
5243 
5244  Designator(DesignatorKind Kind) : Kind(Kind) {}
5245 
5246  public:
5247  Designator() {}
5248 
5249  bool isFieldDesignator() const { return Kind == FieldDesignator; }
5250  bool isArrayDesignator() const { return Kind == ArrayDesignator; }
5251  bool isArrayRangeDesignator() const { return Kind == ArrayRangeDesignator; }
5252 
5253  //===------------------------------------------------------------------===//
5254  // FieldDesignatorInfo
5255 
5256  /// Creates a field designator.
5257  static Designator CreateFieldDesignator(const IdentifierInfo *FieldName,
5258  SourceLocation DotLoc,
5259  SourceLocation FieldLoc) {
5260  Designator D(FieldDesignator);
5261  new (&D.FieldInfo) FieldDesignatorInfo(FieldName, DotLoc, FieldLoc);
5262  return D;
5263  }
5264 
5265  const IdentifierInfo *getFieldName() const;
5266 
5267  FieldDecl *getFieldDecl() const {
5268  assert(isFieldDesignator() && "Only valid on a field designator");
5269  if (FieldInfo.NameOrField & 0x01)
5270  return nullptr;
5271  return reinterpret_cast<FieldDecl *>(FieldInfo.NameOrField);
5272  }
5273 
5274  void setFieldDecl(FieldDecl *FD) {
5275  assert(isFieldDesignator() && "Only valid on a field designator");
5276  FieldInfo.NameOrField = reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(FD);
5277  }
5278 
5279  SourceLocation getDotLoc() const {
5280  assert(isFieldDesignator() && "Only valid on a field designator");
5281  return FieldInfo.DotLoc;
5282  }
5283 
5284  SourceLocation getFieldLoc() const {
5285  assert(isFieldDesignator() && "Only valid on a field designator");
5286  return FieldInfo.FieldLoc;
5287  }
5288 
5289  //===------------------------------------------------------------------===//
5290  // ArrayOrRangeDesignator
5291 
5292  /// Creates an array designator.
5293  static Designator CreateArrayDesignator(unsigned Index,
5294  SourceLocation LBracketLoc,
5295  SourceLocation RBracketLoc) {
5296  Designator D(ArrayDesignator);
5297  new (&D.ArrayOrRangeInfo) ArrayOrRangeDesignatorInfo(Index, LBracketLoc,
5298  RBracketLoc);
5299  return D;
5300  }
5301 
5302  /// Creates a GNU array-range designator.
5303  static Designator CreateArrayRangeDesignator(unsigned Index,
5304  SourceLocation LBracketLoc,
5305  SourceLocation EllipsisLoc,
5306  SourceLocation RBracketLoc) {
5307  Designator D(ArrayRangeDesignator);
5308  new (&D.ArrayOrRangeInfo) ArrayOrRangeDesignatorInfo(Index, LBracketLoc,
5309  EllipsisLoc,
5310  RBracketLoc);
5311  return D;
5312  }
5313 
5314  unsigned getArrayIndex() const {
5315  assert((isArrayDesignator() || isArrayRangeDesignator()) &&
5316  "Only valid on an array or array-range designator");
5317  return ArrayOrRangeInfo.Index;
5318  }
5319 
5320  SourceLocation getLBracketLoc() const {
5321  assert((isArrayDesignator() || isArrayRangeDesignator()) &&
5322  "Only valid on an array or array-range designator");
5323  return ArrayOrRangeInfo.LBracketLoc;
5324  }

5452 /// Represents a place-holder for an object not to be initialized by

5487 // In cases like:
5488 // struct Q { int a, b, c; };
5489 // Q *getQ();
5490 // void foo() {
5491 // struct A { Q q; } a = { *getQ(), .q.b = 3 };
5492 // }
5493 //
5494 // We will have an InitListExpr for a, with type A, and then a
5495 // DesignatedInitUpdateExpr for "a.q" with type Q. The "base" for this DIUE
5496 // is the call expression *getQ(); the "updater" for the DIUE is ".q.b = 3"
5497 //
5498 class DesignatedInitUpdateExpr : public Expr {
5499  // BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0] is the base expression;
5500  // BaseAndUpdaterExprs[1] is an InitListExpr overwriting part of the base.
5501  Stmt *BaseAndUpdaterExprs[2];
5502 
5503 public:
5504  DesignatedInitUpdateExpr(const ASTContext &C, SourceLocation lBraceLoc,
5505  Expr *baseExprs, SourceLocation rBraceLoc);
5506 
5507  explicit DesignatedInitUpdateExpr(EmptyShell Empty)
5508  : Expr(DesignatedInitUpdateExprClass, Empty) { }
5509 
5510  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY;
5511  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY;
5512 
5513  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
5514  return T->getStmtClass() == DesignatedInitUpdateExprClass;
5515  }
5516 
5517  Expr *getBase() const { return cast<Expr>(BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0]); }
5518  void setBase(Expr *Base) { BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0] = Base; }
5519 
5520  InitListExpr *getUpdater() const {
5521  return cast<InitListExpr>(BaseAndUpdaterExprs[1]);
5522  }
5523  void setUpdater(Expr *Updater) { BaseAndUpdaterExprs[1] = Updater; }
5524 
5525  // Iterators
5526  // children = the base and the updater
5527  child_range children() {
5528  return child_range(&BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0], &BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0] + 2);
5529  }
5530  const_child_range children() const {
5531  return const_child_range(&BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0],
5532  &BaseAndUpdaterExprs[0] + 2);
5533  }
5534 };

5536 /// Represents a loop initializing the elements of an array.
5537 ///
5538 /// The need to initialize the elements of an array occurs in a number of
5539 /// contexts:
5540 ///
5541 /// * in the implicit copy/move constructor for a class with an array member
5542 /// * when a lambda-expression captures an array by value
5543 /// * when a decomposition declaration decomposes an array
5544 ///
5545 /// There are two subexpressions: a common expression (the source array)
5546 /// that is evaluated once up-front, and a per-element initializer that
5547 /// runs once for each array element.
5548 ///
5549 /// Within the per-element initializer, the common expression may be referenced
5550 /// via an OpaqueValueExpr, and the current index may be obtained via an
5551 /// ArrayInitIndexExpr.
5552 class ArrayInitLoopExpr : public Expr {
5553  Stmt *SubExprs[2];
5554 
5555  explicit ArrayInitLoopExpr(EmptyShell Empty)
5556  : Expr(ArrayInitLoopExprClass, Empty), SubExprs{} {}
5557 
5558 public:
5559  explicit ArrayInitLoopExpr(QualType T, Expr *CommonInit, Expr *ElementInit)
5560  : Expr(ArrayInitLoopExprClass, T, VK_PRValue, OK_Ordinary),
5561  SubExprs{CommonInit, ElementInit} {
5562  setDependence(computeDependence(this));
5563  }
5564 
5565  /// Get the common subexpression shared by all initializations (the source
5566  /// array).
5567  OpaqueValueExpr *getCommonExpr() const {
5568  return cast<OpaqueValueExpr>(SubExprs[0]);
5569  }
5570 
5571  /// Get the initializer to use for each array element.
5572  Expr *getSubExpr() const { return cast<Expr>(SubExprs[1]); }
5573 
5574  llvm::APInt getArraySize() const {
5575  return cast<ConstantArrayType>(getType()->castAsArrayTypeUnsafe())
5576  ->getSize();
5577  }
5578 
5579  static bool classof(const Stmt *S) {
5580  return S->getStmtClass() == ArrayInitLoopExprClass;
5581  }
5582 
5583  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
5584  return getCommonExpr()->getBeginLoc();
5585  }
5586  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const LLVM_READONLY {
5587  return getCommonExpr()->getEndLoc();
5588  }
5589 
5590  child_range children() {
5591  return child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + 2);
5592  }
5593  const_child_range children() const {
5594  return const_child_range(SubExprs, SubExprs + 2);
5595  }
5596 
5597  friend class ASTReader;
5598  friend class ASTStmtReader;
5599  friend class ASTStmtWriter;
5600 };

5731 /// Represents a C11 generic selection.
5732 ///
5733 /// A generic selection (C11 6.5.1.1) contains an unevaluated controlling
5734 /// expression, followed by one or more generic associations. Each generic
5735 /// association specifies a type name and an expression, or "default" and an
5736 /// expression (in which case it is known as a default generic association).
5737 /// The type and value of the generic selection are identical to those of its
5738 /// result expression, which is defined as the expression in the generic
5739 /// association with a type name that is compatible with the type of the
5740 /// controlling expression, or the expression in the default generic association
5741 /// if no types are compatible. For example:
5742 ///
5743 /// @code
5744 /// _Generic(X, double: 1, float: 2, default: 3)
5745 /// @endcode
5746 ///
5747 /// The above expression evaluates to 1 if 1.0 is substituted for X, 2 if 1.0f
5748 /// or 3 if "hello".
5749 ///
5750 /// As an extension, generic selections are allowed in C++, where the following
5751 /// additional semantics apply:
5752 ///
5753 /// Any generic selection whose controlling expression is type-dependent or
5754 /// which names a dependent type in its association list is result-dependent,
5755 /// which means that the choice of result expression is dependent.
5756 /// Result-dependent generic associations are both type- and value-dependent.
5757 ///
5758 /// We also allow an extended form in both C and C++ where the controlling
5759 /// predicate for the selection expression is a type rather than an expression.
5760 /// This type argument form does not perform any conversions for the
5761 /// controlling type, which makes it suitable for use with qualified type
5762 /// associations, which is not possible with the expression form.
5763 class GenericSelectionExpr final
5764  : public Expr,
5765  private llvm::TrailingObjects<GenericSelectionExpr, Stmt *,
5766  TypeSourceInfo *> {
5767  friend class ASTStmtReader;
5768  friend class ASTStmtWriter;
5769  friend TrailingObjects;
5770 
5771  /// The number of association expressions and the index of the result
5772  /// expression in the case where the generic selection expression is not
5773  /// result-dependent. The result index is equal to ResultDependentIndex
5774  /// if and only if the generic selection expression is result-dependent.
5775  unsigned NumAssocs : 15;
5776  unsigned ResultIndex : 15; // NB: ResultDependentIndex is tied to this width.
5777  LLVM_PREFERRED_TYPE(bool)
5778  unsigned IsExprPredicate : 1;
5779  enum : unsigned {
5780  ResultDependentIndex = 0x7FFF
5781  };
5782 
5783  unsigned getIndexOfControllingExpression() const {
5784  // If controlled by an expression, the first offset into the Stmt *
5785  // trailing array is the controlling expression, the associated expressions
5786  // follow this.
5787  assert(isExprPredicate() && "Asking for the controlling expression of a "
5788  "selection expr predicated by a type");
5789  return 0;
5790  }
5791 
5792  unsigned getIndexOfControllingType() const {
5793  // If controlled by a type, the first offset into the TypeSourceInfo *
5794  // trailing array is the controlling type, the associated types follow this.
5795  assert(isTypePredicate() && "Asking for the controlling type of a "
5796  "selection expr predicated by an expression");
5797  return 0;
5798  }
5799 
5800  unsigned getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs() const {
5801  // If the predicate is a type, then the associated expressions are the only
5802  // Stmt * in the trailing array, otherwise we need to offset past the
5803  // predicate expression.
5804  return (int)isExprPredicate();
5805  }
5806 
5807  unsigned getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedTypes() const {
5808  // If the predicate is a type, then the associated types follow it in the
5809  // trailing array. Otherwise, the associated types are the only
5810  // TypeSourceInfo * in the trailing array.
5811  return (int)isTypePredicate();
5812  }
5813 
5814 
5815  /// The location of the "default" and of the right parenthesis.
5816  SourceLocation DefaultLoc, RParenLoc;
5817 
5818  // GenericSelectionExpr is followed by several trailing objects.
5819  // They are (in order):
5820  //
5821  // * A single Stmt * for the controlling expression or a TypeSourceInfo * for
5822  // the controlling type, depending on the result of isTypePredicate() or
5823  // isExprPredicate().
5824  // * An array of getNumAssocs() Stmt * for the association expressions.
5825  // * An array of getNumAssocs() TypeSourceInfo *, one for each of the
5826  // association expressions.
5827  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<Stmt *>) const {
5828  // Add one to account for the controlling expression; the remainder
5829  // are the associated expressions.
5830  return getNumAssocs() + (int)isExprPredicate();
5831  }
5832 
5833  unsigned numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<TypeSourceInfo *>) const {
5834  // Add one to account for the controlling type predicate, the remainder
5835  // are the associated types.
5836  return getNumAssocs() + (int)isTypePredicate();
5837  }
5838 
5839  template <bool Const> class AssociationIteratorTy;
5840  /// Bundle together an association expression and its TypeSourceInfo.
5841  /// The Const template parameter is for the const and non-const versions
5842  /// of AssociationTy.
5843  template <bool Const> class AssociationTy {
5844  friend class GenericSelectionExpr;
5845  template <bool OtherConst> friend class AssociationIteratorTy;
5846  using ExprPtrTy = std::conditional_t<Const, const Expr *, Expr *>;
5847  using TSIPtrTy =
5848  std::conditional_t<Const, const TypeSourceInfo *, TypeSourceInfo *>;
5849  ExprPtrTy E;
5850  TSIPtrTy TSI;
5851  bool Selected;
5852  AssociationTy(ExprPtrTy E, TSIPtrTy TSI, bool Selected)
5853  : E(E), TSI(TSI), Selected(Selected) {}
5854 
5855  public:
5856  ExprPtrTy getAssociationExpr() const { return E; }
5857  TSIPtrTy getTypeSourceInfo() const { return TSI; }
5858  QualType getType() const { return TSI ? TSI->getType() : QualType(); }
5859  bool isSelected() const { return Selected; }
5860  AssociationTy *operator->() { return this; }
5861  const AssociationTy *operator->() const { return this; }
5862  }; // class AssociationTy
5863 
5864  /// Iterator over const and non-const Association objects. The Association
5865  /// objects are created on the fly when the iterator is dereferenced.
5866  /// This abstract over how exactly the association expressions and the
5867  /// corresponding TypeSourceInfo * are stored.
5868  template <bool Const>
5869  class AssociationIteratorTy
5870  : public llvm::iterator_facade_base<
5871  AssociationIteratorTy<Const>, std::input_iterator_tag,
5872  AssociationTy<Const>, std::ptrdiff_t, AssociationTy<Const>,
5873  AssociationTy<Const>> {
5874  friend class GenericSelectionExpr;
5875  // FIXME: This iterator could conceptually be a random access iterator, and
5876  // it would be nice if we could strengthen the iterator category someday.
5877  // However this iterator does not satisfy two requirements of forward
5878  // iterators:
5879  // a) reference = T& or reference = const T&
5880  // b) If It1 and It2 are both dereferenceable, then It1 == It2 if and only
5881  // if *It1 and *It2 are bound to the same objects.
5882  // An alternative design approach was discussed during review;
5883  // store an Association object inside the iterator, and return a reference
5884  // to it when dereferenced. This idea was discarded beacuse of nasty
5885  // lifetime issues:
5886  // AssociationIterator It = ...;
5887  // const Association &Assoc = *It++; // Oops, Assoc is dangling.
5888  using BaseTy = typename AssociationIteratorTy::iterator_facade_base;
5889  using StmtPtrPtrTy =
5890  std::conditional_t<Const, const Stmt *const *, Stmt **>;
5891  using TSIPtrPtrTy = std::conditional_t<Const, const TypeSourceInfo *const *,
5892  TypeSourceInfo **>;
5893  StmtPtrPtrTy E = nullptr;
5894  TSIPtrPtrTy TSI; // Kept in sync with E.
5895  unsigned Offset = 0, SelectedOffset = 0;
5896  AssociationIteratorTy(StmtPtrPtrTy E, TSIPtrPtrTy TSI, unsigned Offset,
5897  unsigned SelectedOffset)
5898  : E(E), TSI(TSI), Offset(Offset), SelectedOffset(SelectedOffset) {}
5899 
5900  public:
5901  AssociationIteratorTy() : E(nullptr), TSI(nullptr) {}
5902  typename BaseTy::reference operator*() const {
5903  return AssociationTy<Const>(cast<Expr>(*E), *TSI,
5904  Offset == SelectedOffset);
5905  }
5906  typename BaseTy::pointer operator->() const { return **this; }
5907  using BaseTy::operator++;
5908  AssociationIteratorTy &operator++() {
5909  ++E;
5910  ++TSI;
5911  ++Offset;
5912  return *this;
5913  }
5914  bool operator==(AssociationIteratorTy Other) const { return E == Other.E; }
5915  }; // class AssociationIterator
5916 
5917  /// Build a non-result-dependent generic selection expression accepting an
5918  /// expression predicate.
5919  GenericSelectionExpr(const ASTContext &Context, SourceLocation GenericLoc,
5920  Expr *ControllingExpr,
5921  ArrayRef<TypeSourceInfo *> AssocTypes,

5997  using Association = AssociationTy<false>;
5998  using ConstAssociation = AssociationTy<true>;
5999  using AssociationIterator = AssociationIteratorTy<false>;
6000  using ConstAssociationIterator = AssociationIteratorTy<true>;
6001  using association_range = llvm::iterator_range<AssociationIterator>;
6002  using const_association_range =
6003  llvm::iterator_range<ConstAssociationIterator>;
6004 
6005  /// The number of association expressions.
6006  unsigned getNumAssocs() const { return NumAssocs; }
6007 
6008  /// The zero-based index of the result expression's generic association in
6009  /// the generic selection's association list. Defined only if the
6010  /// generic selection is not result-dependent.
6011  unsigned getResultIndex() const {
6012  assert(!isResultDependent() &&
6013  "Generic selection is result-dependent but getResultIndex called!");
6014  return ResultIndex;
6015  }
6016 
6017  /// Whether this generic selection is result-dependent.
6018  bool isResultDependent() const { return ResultIndex == ResultDependentIndex; }
6019 
6020  /// Whether this generic selection uses an expression as its controlling
6021  /// argument.
6022  bool isExprPredicate() const { return IsExprPredicate; }
6023  /// Whether this generic selection uses a type as its controlling argument.
6024  bool isTypePredicate() const { return !IsExprPredicate; }
6025

6027  /// Only valid to call if the selection expression used an expression as its
6028  /// controlling argument.
6029  Expr *getControllingExpr() {
6030  return cast<Expr>(
6031  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>()[getIndexOfControllingExpression()]);
6032  }

6034  return cast<Expr>(
6035  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>()[getIndexOfControllingExpression()]);
6036  }

6039  /// valid to call if the selection expression used a type as its controlling
6040  /// argument.
6041  TypeSourceInfo *getControllingType() {
6042  return getTrailingObjects<TypeSourceInfo *>()[getIndexOfControllingType()];
6043  }
6044  const TypeSourceInfo* getControllingType() const {
6045  return getTrailingObjects<TypeSourceInfo *>()[getIndexOfControllingType()];
6046  }
6047 
6048  /// Return the result expression of this controlling expression. Defined if
6049  /// and only if the generic selection expression is not result-dependent.
6050  Expr *getResultExpr() {
6051  return cast<Expr>(
6052  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>()[getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs() +
6053  getResultIndex()]);
6054  }

6056  return cast<Expr>(
6057  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>()[getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs() +
6058  getResultIndex()]);
6059  }

6061  ArrayRef<Expr *> getAssocExprs() const {
6062  return {reinterpret_cast<Expr *const *>(getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>() +
6063  getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs()),
6064  NumAssocs};
6065  }
6066  ArrayRef<TypeSourceInfo *> getAssocTypeSourceInfos() const {
6067  return {getTrailingObjects<TypeSourceInfo *>() +
6068  getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedTypes(),
6069  NumAssocs};
6070  }
6071 
6072  /// Return the Ith association expression with its TypeSourceInfo,
6073  /// bundled together in GenericSelectionExpr::(Const)Association.
6074  Association getAssociation(unsigned I) {
6075  assert(I < getNumAssocs() &&
6076  "Out-of-range index in GenericSelectionExpr::getAssociation!");
6077  return Association(
6078  cast<Expr>(
6079  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>()[getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs() +
6080  I]),
6081  getTrailingObjects<
6082  TypeSourceInfo *>()[getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedTypes() + I],
6083  !isResultDependent() && (getResultIndex() == I));
6084  }
6085  ConstAssociation getAssociation(unsigned I) const {
6086  assert(I < getNumAssocs() &&
6087  "Out-of-range index in GenericSelectionExpr::getAssociation!");
6088  return ConstAssociation(
6089  cast<Expr>(
6090  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>()[getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs() +
6091  I]),
6092  getTrailingObjects<
6093  TypeSourceInfo *>()[getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedTypes() + I],
6094  !isResultDependent() && (getResultIndex() == I));
6095  }
6096 
6097  association_range associations() {
6098  AssociationIterator Begin(getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>() +
6099  getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs(),
6100  getTrailingObjects<TypeSourceInfo *>() +
6101  getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedTypes(),
6102  /*Offset=*/0, ResultIndex);
6103  AssociationIterator End(Begin.E + NumAssocs, Begin.TSI + NumAssocs,
6104  /*Offset=*/NumAssocs, ResultIndex);
6105  return llvm::make_range(Begin, End);
6106  }
6107 
6108  const_association_range associations() const {
6109  ConstAssociationIterator Begin(getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>() +
6110  getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedExprs(),
6111  getTrailingObjects<TypeSourceInfo *>() +
6112  getIndexOfStartOfAssociatedTypes(),
6113  /*Offset=*/0, ResultIndex);
6114  ConstAssociationIterator End(Begin.E + NumAssocs, Begin.TSI + NumAssocs,
6115  /*Offset=*/NumAssocs, ResultIndex);
6116  return llvm::make_range(Begin, End);
6117  }
6118 
6119  SourceLocation getGenericLoc() const {
6120  return GenericSelectionExprBits.GenericLoc;
6121  }
6122  SourceLocation getDefaultLoc() const { return DefaultLoc; }
6123  SourceLocation getRParenLoc() const { return RParenLoc; }
6124  SourceLocation getBeginLoc() const { return getGenericLoc(); }
6125  SourceLocation getEndLoc() const { return getRParenLoc(); }
6126 
6127  static bool classof(const Stmt *T) {
6128  return T->getStmtClass() == GenericSelectionExprClass;
6129  }
6130 
6131  child_range children() {
6132  return child_range(getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>(),
6133  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>() +
6134  numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<Stmt *>()));
6135  }

6137  return const_child_range(getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>(),
6138  getTrailingObjects<Stmt *>() +
6139  numTrailingObjects(OverloadToken<Stmt *>()));
6140  }
